{
  "Shield volcanoes have gentle slopes because:": "",
  "They erupt explosively": "",
  "They are very small": "",
  "Their low-viscosity basaltic lava flows long distances before solidifying": "",
  "They are ancient and heavily eroded": "",
  "Shield volcanoes like Mauna Loa in Hawaii are built from repeated flows of low-viscosity basaltic lava that can travel great distances. This creates broad, gently sloping structures rather than steep, cone-shaped mountains.": "",
  "The most explosive eruptions come from magma with:": "",
  "High silica content and high viscosity, which traps gas until catastrophic release": "",
  "Equal amounts of all elements": "",
  "Low silica content and low viscosity": "",
  "No dissolved gases": "",
  "High-silica (felsic) magma is very viscous and effectively traps dissolved gases. When this gas-rich magma reaches the surface and pressure drops, the gas expands explosively, fragmenting the magma and producing violent eruptions.": "",
  "Mt. St. Helens (1980) is an example of a:": "",
  "Shield volcano": "",
  "Composite volcano (stratovolcano)": "",
  "Lava dome": "",
  "Cinder cone": "",
  "Mt. St. Helens is a composite volcano (stratovolcano) built from alternating layers of lava flows and explosive volcanic debris. Stratovolcanoes are typically steep-sided and capable of extremely violent eruptions.": "",
  "Pyroclastic flows are extremely dangerous because they:": "",
  "Travel at 100+ km/h at temperatures exceeding 700 degrees C, incinerating everything in their path": "",
  "Only occur underwater, particularly regarding that as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "Move slowly, giving people time to escape under the given assumptions": "",
  "Are cool enough to survive, particularly regarding fast based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "Pyroclastic flows are fast-moving currents of superheated gas and volcanic debris that can reach speeds exceeding 700 km/h and temperatures over 700 degrees C. They are the deadliest volcanic hazard and virtually impossible to outrun.": "",
  "Most volcanoes are found at:": "",
  "Only at the North and South Poles": "",
  "Random locations unrelated to plate tectonics": "",
  "Convergent and divergent plate boundaries": "",
  "The centers of tectonic plates only": "",
  "Most volcanoes occur at plate boundaries: subduction zones at convergent boundaries produce volcanic arcs, and mid-ocean ridges at divergent boundaries produce the most volcanic activity by volume. Hotspot volcanoes within plates are the major exception.": "",
  "Hawaii's volcanoes are located in the middle of the Pacific Plate because of a:": "",
  "Hotspot (mantle plume beneath the Pacific Plate)": "",
  "Transform fault": "",
  "Convergent boundary": "",
  "Divergent boundary": "",
  "Hawaii sits over a stationary mantle hotspot that produces a persistent source of magma. As the Pacific Plate moves northwest over the hotspot, a chain of volcanic islands forms, with the youngest and most active island currently over the plume.": "",
  "A lahar is a volcanic:": "",
  "Lava flow": "",
  "Gas emission": "",
  "Earthquake triggered by magma movement": "",
  "Mudflow made of volcanic debris mixed with water": "",
  "A lahar is a destructive mudflow composed of volcanic debris, ash, and water. Lahars can be triggered by eruptions melting snow and ice, heavy rainfall on ash deposits, or breaching of volcanic lakes. They can travel tens of kilometers and bury communities.": "",
  "The Ring of Fire contains about _____ of the world's active volcanoes.": "",
  "50%": "",
  "About 75%": "",
  "100%": "",
  "25%": "",
  "The Ring of Fire, encircling the Pacific Ocean, contains approximately 75% of the world's active volcanoes. This concentration exists because the Ring of Fire is defined by numerous subduction zones where oceanic plates dive beneath continental plates.": "",
  "Volcanic gases are primarily composed of:": "",
  "Nitrogen and oxygen": "",
  "Water vapor (60-95%), carbon dioxide, and sulfur dioxide": "",
  "Helium and hydrogen": "",
  "Pure carbon dioxide": "",
  "Water vapor is by far the most abundant volcanic gas, comprising 60-95% of emissions. Carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide are the next most common. Sulfur dioxide can form sulfuric acid aerosols in the stratosphere, affecting global climate.": "",
  "The difference between magma and lava is:": "",
  "Their temperature, particularly regarding based": "",
  "Their chemical composition in most standard conditions": "",
  "Their viscosity, particularly regarding rock": "",
  "Their location: magma is underground, lava is at the surface": "",
  "Magma and lava are the same material (molten rock), but the terminology changes based on location. Magma refers to molten rock beneath Earth's surface, while lava refers to molten rock that has erupted and reached the surface.": "",
  "What is a composite volcano (stratovolcano)?": "",
  "A tall, steep-sided volcano built from alternating layers of lava flows and explosive volcanic debris": "",
  "A small, cone-shaped volcano made only of cinder fragments": "",
  "A broad, flat volcano made entirely of lava flows": "",
  "A volcano that has been completely eroded by glaciers": "",
  "Composite volcanoes (stratovolcanoes) are large, steep-sided volcanoes built from alternating layers of lava flows, volcanic ash, and pyroclastic material. They are among the most dangerous volcanoes and include Mt. Fuji, Mt. St. Helens, and Mt. Vesuvius.": "",
  "What is viscosity in the context of volcanic eruptions?": "",
  "The amount of gas dissolved in magma": "",
  "The speed at which lava travels downhill": "",
  "The temperature of magma when it reaches the surface": "",
  "A measure of a fluid's resistance to flow; higher viscosity means the magma flows less easily": "",
  "Viscosity is a measure of how much a fluid resists flowing. In volcanology, magma viscosity is controlled primarily by silica content and temperature. High-silica magma is very viscous (thick and sticky), while low-silica basaltic magma flows easily.": "",
  "What is a caldera?": "",
  "A large, basin-shaped depression formed when a magma chamber empties and the overlying volcano collapses inward": "",
  "A cloud of volcanic ash suspended in the atmosphere": "",
  "A small vent on the side of a volcano": "",
  "A river of lava flowing down the side of a volcano": "",
  "A caldera is a large volcanic depression, typically circular, that forms when the roof of a magma chamber collapses after a massive eruption empties the chamber. Crater Lake in Oregon fills a caldera, and Yellowstone sits atop one of the world's largest calderas.": "",
  "What is tephra?": "",
  "Water heated by volcanic activity": "",
  "Gas that escapes from volcanic vents between eruptions": "",
  "All airborne volcanic material ejected during an eruption, including ash, lapilli, and volcanic bombs": "",
  "Molten rock flowing along the ground": "",
  "Tephra is a general term for all fragments of rock ejected into the air during a volcanic eruption. It is classified by size: ash (less than 2 mm), lapilli (2-64 mm), and volcanic bombs or blocks (greater than 64 mm).": "",
  "What is the Volcanic Explosivity Index (VEI)?": "",
  "A scale that measures the temperature of lava": "",
  "A measure of how often a volcano erupts per century": "",
  "A scale that measures earthquake magnitude near volcanoes": "",
  "A logarithmic scale from 0 to 8 that classifies volcanic eruptions by their explosive magnitude based on volume of material ejected": "",
  "The VEI is a relative scale that ranges from 0 (non-explosive) to 8 (mega-colossal). Each step represents roughly a tenfold increase in ejected material. VEI-8 eruptions, like Yellowstone's ancient super-eruptions, eject over 1,000 cubic kilometers of material.": "",
  "What is a cinder cone volcano?": "",
  "The largest type of volcano, with gently sloping sides": "",
  "A small, steep-sided volcano built from fragments of volcanic rock ejected during mildly explosive eruptions": "",
  "A volcano that only erupts underwater": "",
  "A volcano formed by two continental plates colliding": "",
  "Cinder cone volcanoes are the smallest and simplest type, built from piles of volcanic cinders and bombs ejected from a single vent. They have steep sides and are typically short-lived. Paricutin in Mexico, which grew in a farmer's field in 1943, is a famous example.": "",
  "What does 'pyroclastic' mean?": "",
  "A type of volcanic rock formed underwater": "",
  "Literally 'fire-broken,' referring to hot fragments of rock produced by explosive volcanic eruptions": "",
  "Related to volcanic gas emissions": "",
  "Related to the slow flow of lava over flat terrain": "",
  "The term pyroclastic comes from the Greek words 'pyro' (fire) and 'klastos' (broken). Pyroclastic material includes all hot, fragmented rock produced during explosive eruptions, from fine ash to large boulders.": "",
  "What is a shield volcano?": "",
  "A small, steep-sided volcano built from explosive eruptions": "",
  "A broad, gently sloping volcano built primarily from fluid basaltic lava flows that spread over wide areas": "",
  "A dormant volcano covered by a thick ice cap": "",
  "A volcano surrounded by a wall of rock for protection": "",
  "Shield volcanoes are the largest volcanoes by volume, with broad, gently sloping profiles that resemble a warrior's shield. They are built almost entirely from numerous thin flows of fluid basaltic lava. Mauna Loa in Hawaii is the world's largest active shield volcano.": "",
  "What is a pyroclastic flow?": "",
  "A cloud of volcanic gas that rises into the stratosphere": "",
  "A fast-moving avalanche of superheated gas, ash, and rock fragments that races down a volcano's slopes": "",
  "A slow-moving stream of lava": "",
  "A river of volcanic mud triggered by heavy rain": "",
  "A pyroclastic flow is a ground-hugging avalanche of hot gas, ash, pumice, and rock fragments that can travel at speeds exceeding 700 km/h with temperatures above 700 degrees C. They are the most lethal volcanic hazard and the flow that destroyed Pompeii in 79 AD.": "",
  "What is volcanic monitoring?": "",
  "Watching volcanoes only with binoculars from a safe distance": "",
  "The systematic use of seismographs, GPS, gas analyzers, satellites, and other tools to detect signs of impending eruptions": "",
  "Counting the number of volcanoes on Earth": "",
  "Predicting exactly when a volcano will erupt down to the hour": "",
  "Volcanic monitoring uses multiple tools to track changes that precede eruptions: increased seismicity, ground deformation (swelling), changes in gas emissions, and thermal anomalies. While exact eruption timing cannot be predicted, monitoring provides crucial early warnings.": "",
  "A community is located 30 km from a large stratovolcano. The local government is developing a hazard plan. Based on the characteristics of stratovolcanoes, which hazard should they prioritize planning for?": "",
  "Lahars (volcanic mudflows) that can travel far from the volcano at high speed, especially along river valleys": "",
  "Slow-moving lava flows that can be easily diverted": "",
  "Acid rain that only occurs during eruptions": "",
  "Lava fountains that only affect the summit area": "",
  "At 30 km from a stratovolcano, lahars are the most likely hazard to reach the community. Lahars can travel over 50 km from a volcano following river valleys at speeds up to 60 km/h, burying communities in volcanic mud. Many stratovolcanoes are snow-capped, providing water to generate lahars during eruptions.": "",
  "In 1991, volcanologists predicted the eruption of Mt. Pinatubo in the Philippines, and over 200,000 people were evacuated, saving an estimated 20,000 lives. What monitoring data most likely triggered the evacuation order?": "",
  "Satellite images showing lava flowing from the summit": "",
  "Historical records indicating the volcano erupts every 100 years": "",
  "A sudden drop in the surrounding ocean temperature": "",
  "Increasing earthquake swarms beneath the volcano, ground deformation, and rising sulfur dioxide emissions indicating magma rising toward the surface": "",
  "The successful prediction of the Mt. Pinatubo eruption relied on detecting a combination of precursory signals: escalating seismic activity, measurable ground swelling, and sharply increasing sulfur dioxide gas emissions. Together, these indicators pointed to magma ascending toward the surface.": "",
  "After the 1815 eruption of Mt. Tambora, global temperatures dropped by about 0.5 degrees C, leading to the 'Year Without a Summer' in 1816. Crop failures occurred across Europe and North America. How did a single volcanic eruption affect global climate?": "",
  "The eruption directly froze the atmosphere with cold lava": "",
  "The ash from the eruption blocked rivers, causing floods that cooled the planet": "",
  "Massive amounts of sulfur dioxide injected into the stratosphere formed sulfuric acid aerosols that reflected sunlight, reducing the solar energy reaching Earth's surface": "",
  "The eruption depleted atmospheric oxygen, preventing heat from being generated": "",
  "Tambora injected an enormous amount of sulfur dioxide into the stratosphere, where it formed sulfuric acid aerosols. These tiny particles reflected incoming solar radiation back into space, reducing global temperatures and disrupting weather patterns for over a year.": "",
  "A real estate developer wants to build a resort community on the fertile slopes of an active composite volcano, citing the excellent soil quality. What scientific risk assessment should be communicated to potential buyers?": "",
  "Insurance will cover any volcanic damage, so risk assessment is unnecessary": "",
  "There is no risk because the soil quality proves the volcano is extinct": "",
  "Volcanic soil is fertile because of past eruptions, and the same processes that enriched the soil pose ongoing risks including pyroclastic flows, lahars, ashfall, and lava flows": "",
  "The only risk is occasional bad smells from volcanic gas": "",
  "The fertile soil near volcanoes is a direct product of volcanic ash weathering into nutrient-rich material. However, the same volcanic activity that creates this soil also poses serious hazards. Active composite volcanoes can produce destructive eruptions with little warning.": "",
  "Two volcanoes erupt at the same time: Volcano A produces thin, fast-flowing lava, while Volcano B explodes violently, sending an ash column 30 km into the atmosphere. What difference in magma composition most likely explains these contrasting eruption styles?": "",
  "Volcano A is on land while Volcano B is underwater": "",
  "Both have the same magma, but Volcano B is at higher elevation": "",
  "Volcano A has low-silica basaltic magma with low viscosity, while Volcano B has high-silica felsic magma that traps gas and erupts explosively": "",
  "Volcano A has hotter magma, while Volcano B has cooler magma": "",
  "Silica content is the primary control on eruption style. Low-silica basaltic magma is fluid and allows gas to escape easily, producing effusive eruptions with flowing lava. High-silica felsic magma is viscous and traps gas, leading to explosive eruptions when the pressure is finally released.": "",
  "Yellowstone National Park sits atop a massive magma chamber that last produced a super-eruption 640,000 years ago. Scientists continuously monitor the area. If they detected a significant increase in ground uplift, earthquake frequency, and helium emissions, what would these signals suggest?": "",
  "The area is experiencing normal seasonal changes": "",
  "The data indicates that an eruption is impossible at Yellowstone": "",
  "The volcano is becoming dormant and shutting down": "",
  "Fresh magma may be rising into the chamber, increasing the potential for volcanic activity": "",
  "Ground uplift, increased seismicity, and elevated gas emissions are classic precursory signals of magma movement. While these signs do not necessarily mean an eruption is imminent, they indicate that magma is actively moving, requiring heightened monitoring and public communication.": "",
  "An airline pilot flying over the Pacific receives a volcanic ash advisory warning of an eruption 500 km away. Even at that distance, the pilot diverts the aircraft. Why is volcanic ash so dangerous to aircraft, even far from the eruption?": "",
  "The ash blocks radio communications but poses no physical danger": "",
  "Volcanic ash is only dangerous within 10 km of the eruption": "",
  "Volcanic ash only affects propeller aircraft, not jets": "",
  "Fine volcanic ash can travel thousands of kilometers, and when ingested by jet engines it melts, coats turbine blades, and can cause engine failure": "",
  "Volcanic ash consists of tiny, sharp glass and mineral fragments that can remain suspended in the atmosphere for days and travel thousands of kilometers. In jet engines, ash melts at combustion temperatures, coats turbine blades, and can cause catastrophic engine failure.": "",
  "The island of Montserrat in the Caribbean has been dramatically affected by ongoing eruptions of the Soufriere Hills volcano since 1995. The capital city, Plymouth, was completely buried by pyroclastic flows and lahars. What type of volcano is Soufriere Hills, and why is it so dangerous?": "",
  "It is a shield volcano that produces dangerous lava flows": "",
  "It is a stratovolcano that produces explosive eruptions, pyroclastic flows, and lahars due to its high-silica magma": "",
  "It is a dormant volcano that is not truly dangerous": "",
  "It is a cinder cone that produces only mild ash emissions": "",
  "Soufriere Hills is a stratovolcano that erupts viscous, gas-rich andesitic to dacitic magma. This produces explosive eruptions, dome collapses that generate pyroclastic flows, and lahars. Its location on a small, densely populated island amplifies the impact.": "",
  "Farmers living near Mount Vesuvius in Italy continue to cultivate the volcanic soil despite the volcano's history of catastrophic eruptions, including the destruction of Pompeii in 79 AD. What trade-off are these farmers making?": "",
  "They benefit from extremely fertile volcanic soil that supports productive agriculture, but accept the risk of future eruptions from one of the world's most dangerous volcanoes": "",
  "The soil is not actually volcanic; it was transported from elsewhere": "",
  "There is no trade-off because Vesuvius will never erupt again": "",
  "The Italian government guarantees complete protection from eruptions": "",
  "This illustrates a fundamental human-volcano trade-off. Weathered volcanic ash produces exceptionally fertile soil rich in minerals and nutrients, supporting intensive agriculture. However, about 3 million people live in the potential danger zone of Vesuvius, and another major eruption is considered inevitable.": "",
  "During the 2010 eruption of Eyjafjallajokull in Iceland, a relatively small eruption (VEI 4) caused the cancellation of over 100,000 flights across Europe, affecting 10 million travelers. How can a moderate eruption have such far-reaching consequences?": "",
  "The eruption generated earthquakes that damaged airports": "",
  "Prevailing winds carried the volcanic ash cloud over busy European airspace, and the ash hazard to jet engines forced unprecedented airspace closures": "",
  "The eruption sent lava flows across the Atlantic Ocean": "",
  "The eruption was misidentified as much larger than it actually was": "",
  "Iceland's location along the jet stream meant that prevailing winds carried the fine ash cloud directly over some of the world's busiest airspace. Even a moderate eruption can inject enough fine ash into high-altitude wind patterns to create a hazard covering thousands of square kilometers.": ""
}